    55	| **Monthly-average alternative** | §20-563.3(a)/(b)/(d): the cap may be satisfied on the calendar-month average — Σ(fees in month) ≤ cap% × Σ(purchase prices in month) — instead of per order. The transaction fee (c) has no averaging alternative. | Passing the cap on the month's average instead of every single order — allowed for three of the four fee types, never for the 3% processing fee. |
    56	| **One-page report (S-9)** | The verifier's output as a single self-contained document — evidence-cited, spec-version pinned, simulated-labeled — rendered two ways over the SAME data: a machine-JSON leg (CLI) and a web view (`/report`). "One page" means one cohesive, printable document per report, not a hard one-physical-page cap; every finding's four receipts stay visible (C2 forbids hiding them), and the print stylesheet keeps a finding from splitting across a page break. | The result written up as one readable (and printable) page — plain sentence per catch, receipts beside it — nothing hidden to make it fit. |
    57	| **Orchestration harness passed** | The ONLY label an offline trajectory replay can earn (plan §6): the crew's containment machinery (tool gating at the call site, demo/advisory refusal, human-gate forcing, finding-reference validation) held on every committed case, with model turns replayed from a committed fixture. Explicitly NOT the "agent" label — that requires the owner-gated live run (L-1) clearing the same per-member floors on a held-out split. | "The rails and brakes all work." It says nothing yet about the driver — the AI wasn't really driving. |
    58	| **Over-cap refund safe harbor** | §20-563.3(e): an over-cap charge under subdivisions a/b/d is not a violation if the excess is refunded within 30 calendar days of the final day of the month of the charge; subdivision c (transaction fee) is excluded. | A 30-day grace window to refund an overcharge — except on the 3% processing fee, which gets no grace at all. |
    59	| **Pre-build crux gate (G8)** | The hard gate (Codex amendment 1) that blocks UC-2 implementation until the two-part crux is resolved: (i) does a copy layer persist behind live catalog reads in marketplaces? (ii) who has authority/pain/budget to require independent truth evidence? | Before building, we must prove the problem will still exist (copies keep drifting) and that someone would actually run the tool. |
    60	| **Capture-then-replay (L-1)** | The live-run mechanic that keeps shipped code untouched: each live model decision is fetched ONCE and recorded, then the authoritative trajectory record is produced by re-running the UNCHANGED orchestrator (`runCase`) with those recorded decisions — the same code path as the offline replay. The committed raw turns make the whole result re-derivable offline forever (`l1-live-lock`). | The AI's answers are written on cards first; then the exact same exam machine that ran the practice test runs them — so the "live" grade can be re-checked any time without calling the AI again. |
    61	| **Deterministic param mapper (L-1)** | The §6-addendum rule that a live model never authors tool parameters: its decision surface is a closed vocabulary (pick a tool / reject; approve / escalate), and parameters derive mechanically from the tool name + the case's committed artifact path. The mapper never reads the case's expected calls, so the orchestrator's digest containment independently verifies mapper ≡ contract. | The AI may only point at which button to press — the machine fills in the button's settings itself, from a fixed rulebook the AI can't touch. |
    62	| **Pre-registration (calibration)** | Pinning the pass/fail floors, decision rule, and harness semantics in a committed doc BEFORE a live run executes; floors may only ever tighten pre-run, never move after results are seen; a missed floor ⇒ the label DEFERS (no same-split re-run under the 2026-07-04 arming amendment). | Writing the grading rules down before the exam, in ink — so the bar can't move once the score is known. |
    63	| **Precision / recall** | Precision: of the items flagged, the fraction truly wrong. Recall: of the items truly wrong, the fraction flagged. | Precision = how often the alarm is right. Recall = how many real problems the alarm catches. |
    64	| **Print stylesheet** | A CSS `@media print` block that restyles a page for paper/PDF output — here it hides the nav, footer, and surface toggle, forces the honesty labels and severity colors to print (`print-color-adjust: exact`), and marks each finding `break-inside: avoid` so a catch and its receipts never split across a page break. | The extra styling that makes the on-screen report print to a clean page, with the "simulated" label always visible. |
    65	| **Purchase price base** | "Purchase price of each online order" — the statutory base every cap percentage is measured against (§20-563.3(a)–(d)). Its inclusions/exclusions (tax, tip, pre- vs post-discount) are UNVERIFIED as of 2026-07-03 (source-memo U1) — base-derived verdicts are provisional until resolved. | The order amount the percentages apply to — with an honest asterisk: exactly what counts inside it is still an open question. |
    66	| **Reconciliation** | The operational process of comparing two independent records of the same activity (e.g., POS sales vs platform payout statement) and explaining every difference. | Lining up two versions of the books and accounting for every mismatch, penny by penny. |
    67	| **Recorded model turn** | A committed, typed decision (`evals/crew/cases/recorded-turns.json`) replayed in place of a live model call during offline trajectory evaluation; an unplanned turn throws loudly rather than defaulting. Steered/hostile recorded turns deliberately simulate a compromised model so what gets measured is the ORCHESTRATOR'S containment. | The "AI's answer" comes from a checked-in answer sheet — including some deliberately WRONG answers, to prove the guardrails catch a misbehaving AI. |
    68	| **Refund-window verdict state** | The disposition F1a assigns an over-cap on a/b/d, encoded (not prose): `violation` (window closed, no covering refund), `conditional-pending-refund-window` (window still open — not yet a violation), or `cured-by-refund` (refunded in time — not a violation). The transaction fee (c) has no such state — it is a violation immediately (no §20-563.3(e) safe harbor). | Whether an overcharge is a settled violation, still inside the legal refund-grace clock, or already refunded and cleared — a real state, not a fixed yes/no. |
    69	| **SOR (system-of-record)** | The authoritative data source for a fact domain — the merchant's POS/catalog for menu truth, the payout ledger for money truth — against which every served copy or statement line is verified. | The one place that holds the *real* answer — the till, not the app's copy. |
    70	| **Spec-faithful demonstration actor** | The D1 demo's scripted stand-in agent — labeled "spec-faithful demonstration actor — simulated." It consumes ONLY the published serving copy (its transitive imports are machine-proven to exclude the SOR reference resolver and every SOR fixture — SOR-blindness), applies one fixed scripted intent, and selects the target item at the copy's face value. Deterministic, $0, no LLM; the demo ends at selection (slice-C cut, no checkout). | A rule-following pretend shopping agent that only ever sees the published menu (never the restaurant's till), decides by a fixed rule, and believes whatever the menu says — used to show the drift it can't detect. |
    71	| **Synthetic data** | Deliberately constructed data (including adversarial edge cases), clearly labeled as simulated, used for demos and eval coverage. | Made-up test data — labeled as such — built to include the tricky cases real data rarely shows on demand. |
    72	| **Take-rate (effective)** | The total share of merchant revenue a platform captures once all fees (commission, processing, marketing, promos, refund costs) are included — vs the headline commission. | What the platform *really* takes, not the advertised percentage. |
    73	| **Tool envelope** | The typed, frozen result every A0 registry tool returns (`ToolResult`, `lib/tools/types.ts`): which tool ran, whether it passed (`ok`, defined as `exitCode === 0` — enforced at construction), its exit code, the honesty flags a consumer must never miss (`demoOnly` on `run_demo`; `advisory`/`earnsLabel` on `classify_and_audit`), and `canonical` — the tool's own named-serializer string output. | The same-shaped little receipt every tool hands back — which tool ran, did it pass, and (when it matters) a flashing "this is a demo" or "this is just a suggestion" flag. |
    74	| **Tool registry** | The A0 seam (`lib/tools/registry.ts`): six typed JSON-in/JSON-out tools (`check_feed`, `check_conformance`, `audit_statement`, `classify_and_audit`, `get_rule`, `run_demo`), each wrapping an UNCHANGED engine entry point with a committed input/output JSON Schema. `callTool(name, params)` validates `params` against the tool's schema via ajv BEFORE running it — invalid input fails loud with a typed `ToolInputError`; an unregistered name fails loud with `ToolNotFoundError`. This is the ONE call surface every later surface (MCP server, agent crew, delivery builders, n8n lane) is meant to consume, so they can never bypass the engine's own validation and error discipline. | The one panel of six clearly-labeled buttons every future robot (an AI agent, an automation workflow) presses instead of reaching into the checker's engine room directly — press the wrong button, or press it with a wrong-shaped input, and it refuses loudly instead of guessing. |
    75	| **ToS-clean access** | Reading data only through channels the terms of service permit: public documents, one's own accounts/sandboxes, and merchant-permissioned APIs — never scraping walled surfaces. | Only looking where we're allowed to look. |
    76	| **Trajectory case** | One committed JSON document (schema in `docs/plan-a2-trajectory-floors.md`) specifying a crew run's contract and expectations: input artifact, allowed/forbidden tools, the exact expected executed tool-call sequence (with sha256 argument digests), the expected engine-report hash, recommendation class, finding references, and gate state. The unit the §6 floors are measured on; "the injection does not steer tool choice" is DEFINED as the actual sequence still matching this document. | One exam question for the helper team, written down and locked before the exam — what it's given, what it may touch, and exactly what a right answer looks like. |
    77	| **Transaction fee** | NYC §20-563.3(c): the card-processing-type fee; capped at 3% of the purchase price per order — no monthly averaging, no refund safe harbor; above 3% only as an exact, documented pass-through of the actual processor charge, with proof available to the department and the establishment on request. | The card-processing fee — a hard 3%, unless they can prove every cent above it is a pure pass-through of real cost. |
    78	| **Tune/test split** | A disjoint partition of a gold set: iteration/threshold-tuning happens ONLY on the *tune* half; every reported claim is scored ONLY on the held-out *test* half. F1b's fee-lines gold set pins 21/21 with per-class stratification and a composition test enforcing the discipline. | Practice questions vs the real exam — you may study the first pile all you want, but your grade only ever comes from the second. |
    79	| **UCP (Universal Commerce Protocol)** | Google-led open agentic-commerce spec (unveiled 2026-01-11 at NRF; Apache-2.0; spec 2026-04-08 live at ucp.dev/GitHub; RFC-2119 normative language). Food vertical co-developed by DoorDash, Square, Toast, Uber Eats — food schemas pending. Catalog capability is a LIVE-QUERY interface (session-scoped), not a static feed. | The Google-side standard AI assistants use to shop and order. Its menu-lookup part asks the store live, rather than reading a saved copy — which matters for what can drift. |
